{"title_page": "The Soul Collector", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Soul Collector \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| based_on             = [[Maureen Child|Kathleen Kane]] (book)\n| writer               = Joyce Brotman\n| director             = Michael M. Scott\n| starring             = [[Bruce Greenwood]]<br>[[Melissa Gilbert]]<br>[[Hilary Duff]]<br>[[Ossie Davis]]<br>[[Scotty Leavenworth]]<br>[[Brent Anderson]]\n| music                = Dan Foliart\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| executive_producer   = Marian Brayton<br>Anne Carlucci\n| producer             = Bill Scott\n| editor               = Andrew London\n| cinematography       = [[Don E. Fauntleroy]]\n| runtime              = 93 minutes\n| company              = [[Hearst Communications|Hearst Entertainment Productions]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1999|10|24}}\n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''The Soul Collector''''' is a 1999 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[romantic fantasy]]-[[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by Michael M. Scott.\n\n==Plot==\nZach ([[Bruce Greenwood]]) is a soul collector: an [[angel]] who collects souls to take up to heaven. He is sent to earth to live as a human for thirty days on a [[Texas]] [[cattle]] [[ranch]]. There, he falls in love with ranch owner Rebecca ([[Melissa Gilbert]]), a widowed single mother, and influences the lives of her son and the ranch workers.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Bruce Greenwood]] as Zacariah\n*[[Melissa Gilbert]] as Rebecca\n*[[Hilary Duff]] as Ellie\n*[[Ossie Davis]] as Mordecai\n*[[Scotty Leavenworth]] as Danny\n*[[Brent Anderson]] as Sam Scott\n*[[Buck Taylor]] as Charlie\n*[[Clayton Adams]] as Bartender\n\n==Reception==\n''[[OK!]]'' summed it up: \"An angel (Bruce Greenwood) chooses life on Earth as a human being, falls for a widow and is zapped by the emotions that we weepy mortals take for granted. ''[[City of Angels (film)|City of Angels]]!'' we hear you cry \u2013 true, but this is better.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Bruno|last=MacDonald|title=Movie choice|magazine=[[OK!]]|date=May 26, 2000}}</ref>\n\n==DVD release==\n[[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]] announced ''The Soul Collector'' on DVD.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0203933|title=The Soul Collector}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soul Collector}}\n[[Category:1999 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Films set in Texas]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Soul Collector \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| based_on             = [[Maureen Child|Kathleen Kane]] (book)\n| writer               = Joyce Brotman\n| director             = Michael M. Scott\n| starring             = [[Bruce Greenwood]]<br>[[Melissa Gilbert]]<br>[[Hilary Duff]]<br>[[Ossie Davis]]<br>[[Scotty Leavenworth]]<br>[[Brent Anderson]]\n| music                = Dan Foliart\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| executive_producer   = Marian Brayton<br>Anne Carlucci\n| producer             = Bill Scott\n| editor               = Andrew London\n| cinematography       = [[Don E. Fauntleroy]]\n| runtime              = 93 minutes\n| company              = [[Hearst Communications|Hearst Entertainment Productions]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1999|10|24}}\n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''The Soul Collector''''' is a 1999 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[romantic fantasy]]-[[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by Michael M. Scott.\n\n==Plot==\nZach ([[Bruce Greenwood]]) is a soul collector: an [[angel]] who collects souls to take up to heaven. He is sent to earth to live as a human for thirty days on a [[Texas]] [[cattle]] [[ranch]]. There, he falls in love with ranch owner Rebecca ([[Melissa Gilbert]]), a widowed single mother, and influences the lives of her son and the ranch workers.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Bruce Greenwood]] as Zacariah\n*[[Melissa Gilbert]] as Rebecca\n*[[Hilary Duff]] as Ellie\n*[[Ossie Davis]] as Mordecai\n*[[Scotty Leavenworth]] as Danny\n*[[Brent Anderson]] as Sam Scott\n*[[Buck Taylor]] as Charlie\n*[[Clayton Adams]] as Bartender\n\n==Reception==\n''[[OK!]]'' summed it up: \"An angel (Bruce Greenwood) chooses life on Earth as a human being, falls for a widow and is zapped by the emotions that we weepy mortals take for granted. ''[[City of Angels (film)|City of Angels]]!'' we hear you cry \u2013 true, but this is better.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Bruno|last=MacDonald|title=Movie choice|magazine=[[OK!]]|date=May 26, 2000}}</ref>\n\n==DVD release==\n[[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]] announced ''The Soul Collector'' on DVD.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0203933|title=The Soul Collector}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soul Collector}}\n[[Category:1999 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Films set in Texas]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Soul_Collector"}
